Introduction

Milliman PRM Analytics is a predictive analytics solution capable of predicting any number of healthcare management risks. The primary predictive analytics are the Opportunity Prospective Scores.

Milliman PRM Analytics is not a standalone solution. It can also be integrated with an existing care management system for comprehensive care management. The PRM Care Coordinator Reports provide care managers with a comprehensive view of recent patient clinical and claims activity, making management more efficient and effective.

Milliman PRM Analytics are backed by more than 65 years of experience in healthcare consulting, data analytics, operational analysis and problem solving. The solutions offered by this tool leverage a unique reporting structure and custom analytics that help meet coming healthcare challenges head on.

This user guide is designed to give users an understanding of the latest features of the PRM Project Management Console (PMC) and step by step instructions for using the system.

Note: Please note that these instructions are ONLY meant for users who have been granted access.

Functionality is dictated by what was enabled for the role assigned to the user and the options enabled for the client. For illustration purposes, all of the functionality is enabled in the screen shots shown below.

PRM Project Management Console

Overview

Millframe 4.1.0 consists of five modules, and Web Portal is one of those. The PRM Web Portal module allows the client users to view the reports for the group(s) they are associated with. The application also allows the Client User Administrators to launch Client User Administration Console application, and the Client Publishers to launch Client Publisher Console application.

Definitions

Group – an arbitrary container used to associate Users to Reports (QVWs).

The PMC is used to manage Projects and Reports for Groups.

Signature – extra attributes attached to a QVW (Report) that identifies a specific Group the report may be associated with via the Project Management Console.

The goal of a Signature is to keep a User who is running the Project Management Console from accidentally putting a Report into the wrong Group and having PHI sent to Users in a different Group who shouldn’t have access to it.

Analytics Pipeline – Onboarding, translation/transformation, or processing code used to calculate value-added data and binding data onto a QVW (Report) that is signed (Signature) for a specific Group.

The Analytics Pipeline is the side that generates the Reports. The data is processed and turned into value-added fields which are bound onto a QlikView interface which results in a QVW (Report).

The QVW is then signed and that Signature is carried along with it and dictates certain things about that Report and provides security for the data, which flows from the Analytics Pipeline to the security framework of PRM.

Signature Tool

  1. The Signature Tool is a tool that allows the user to view how a Report is signed. Since this Test Report is already, we will use the tool to view the Signature.

  1. So we click to open the Signature Tool.

  1. Next we click on Test Project

  1. Next we look inside at the information contained in the Signature.

  1. This is custom code, the same code used in the Analytics Pipeline. It has a command line interface, where you can call and update this information. When you look at a Signature, the security framework understands that when you have keys that begin with a @ sign, you should concatenate all these lines together. This is this case what you are trying to do is to create a Group code. This group is called 0273SCH01TEST2. This dictates the directory that this Report can go into. Let us look at some other keys.

  • can_emit. This asks “Does this QlikView report contain all the extra scripts in the QVW that allows the security framework to determine hierarchical information inside report so it can do loop and reduce or it can reduce a view of the report down. The primary use of this key is to allow a User account to be associated with a sub-set of data in the Report. SO, if the value of can_emit is set to True, then we have the capability of allowing a User to be associated with a sub-set of date in the Report. Since the value here is set to False, it means that ALL the Users will always see ALL the data all the time.

  • ariber_security. Since currently there is one security framework, we always set this to Milliman. If you had a client with multiple security frameworks, then those values would be added to the Signature.

  • can_verify. This signifies that there is another script in the QVW that allows us to look at what is inside the QVW once it has been reduced. So, for example, if you come in and say, “User A can only see Providers B&C, the can_verify script says “Another association has been made, we’ve reduced the QVW down and now if I look back inside the QVW as part of the auditing process, I can verify that Providers B&C are still the only 2 providers that User A can see. Basically, it allows auditing of the QVW once it has been produced.

Project Management Console

NOTE: By default, the Project Management Console is run in Firefox, but for the purposes of this guide, we will be using Internet Explorer.

  1. First we log into the PMC.

  1. Then we go into the folders which are set up a lot like File Explorer.

  1. You drill down to a leaf node and eventually get to a Project. In this case our Project is hciprj.

  1. There is information here in the User Interface. There is a Refresh button on top. You use this when importing new information into the Project.

  1. You call also tell it to create a new Directory.

  1. We will call this directory Test7.

  1. Once created, the Test7 folder appears.

  1. You can also use the red X to delete a folder. There are certain ramifications in deleting a folder which will be discussed at a later time.

  1. Last, you can click the green icon with the black center dot on the right to create a Project from a signed QVW. This is essentially the Import feature.

  1. This is the way we bring all of the QVWs into the security framework for the first time. After that we do updates on a monthly or bi-monthly basis.

  2. Before exploring the Import feature, let’s go back to the folder tree.

  1. Once you go to the folder you have created and right-click, you are given 3 options:

  • Delete (like the option above)

  • Create a New Folder and

  • Create a Project

  1. The purpose of this option is to allow the User to create a new Project inside this folder. So we click on folder Test7 and Create Project.

  1. A dialogue box appears with a number of fields that the User can fill out.

  1. The end result of filling out the dialogue box is the creation of an nciprj file being saved in this directory named Test7.

  1. The way this is typically done is using the previously mentioned Import.

  1. The Create Folder and Create a Project method was the original way the system was set up. As the system evolved, it was decided that from a security standpoint it would be better for the files to be created from projects with existing security codes.

  1. So essentially the nciprj Project file is like an envelope that contains all the report and security code information listed in the Signature and is linked to a specific Group by using a specific Client Code and the directory structure.

  1. When this information is pushed to the Production machine, all this information, it makes sure that the Test QVW (report) with this specific Signature can only be sent to the specific Group 0273SC01TEST2 .

  2. The Signature also dictates where the Report sits in the directory structure.

  3. Only Users associated with Group 0273SC01TEST2 will be able to see this Report.

  4. The remaining values in the Signature, can_emit and can_verify describe other capabilities the security framework has.

Additional Functions of the Project Management Console

  1. Right-clicking on the Project folder reveals an additional Options menu.

  1. Delete would remove the Project from the Group. The Group and associated Users would remain intact but with no associated Report.

  1. Whoever is running the PMC isn’t running it on the Production machine. The Production machine has a copy from previous posts. Clicking on Diff Local/ Server Projects allows Users to see if someone has come in locally on this machine since the last time and updated this project.

  1. In this example, the value for Local/Server is equal.

  1. Clicking Diff Local/ Server Projects for the details, we see that the values for each option are indeed equal.

  1. So scrolling down and checking all the values, you know that the local version and the copy on the server are both the same.

  2. The next menu item, Publishing History provides a record of each time the Project was modified.

  1. Opening up the dialogue box reveals the last time the Project was published and who published it.

  1. This was just the initial version. As people publish more versions, those are added to the list and we can go back and look at who is publishing and what those versions look like.

  2. The next item, Edit Project Settings is the same as when we clicked on the folder tree on the left.

  1. So when we click on Edit Project Settings the dialogue box pops up

  1. The Project name is the same as the original hciprj name and the QVW is name of the Report itself.

  1. The Project Description actually appears on the Web Portal.

  1. Project Notes is a field to add notes. Project Tooltip also appears in the Web Portal and provides the User with additional information when you mouse-over the Report.

  1. The Thumbnail is a miniature picture of the project in either .jpg, .gif or .png format.

  2. There is a place mark currently for a User Guide link titled User Manual.

  1. At the bottom of the box is a list of the Groups. As seen previously, our group was checked automatically since it was Imported. However, you can edit any of the information in this dialogue box as needed and hit the Save button. The new information will be updated in the SCH Test2.hciprj.

  1. Next is the menu item Reset Project. This setting takes the project you have on the Local machine and will reset the content to match what is on the Production machine.

  1. The reason for this setting is that, with more complex postings, things can go wrong and the Project Management Console goes out-of-synch from what is on the Production machine. At this point, you have the option to reset what is on the Local machine to match the content on the Production machine, which is the “source of Truth.”

  2. When you hit the Reset Project button, you will have a chance to do the reset or cancel.

A reset process looks like this:

This is the reset confirmation:

  1. The next option is Re-populate QVW.

  1. When you Re-populate QVW, the box appears and allows you to create a new report. It also gives you the option to add a User Manual.

  1. Ignore the section called Add New Download Items. It will be going away in future releases of the PMC.

  2. Once you have the information you need, you hit the Update Project button. And you will receive a confirmation message.

  1. Since can_emit in the Signature is set to False, all Users will see all the data all the time and there is nothing else for the PMC to do other than associate the Report.

  2. Next you hit Push and the Report show up. You then verify that all the information is correct.

  1. The tabs on the top of this screen deal with Reduction and will be discussed in a future release of the User Guide.

  2. Everything that has been done up to this point is all local until you hit the Publish to Production button at the bottom of the screen.

  1. This takes what is Local and moves it to the Production machine. It re- associates things and moves them to the server.

  1. When complete you receive a confirmation message.

  1. When this is complete, there are also emails that are pushed out and a report of the record is published. The emails contain a table like the report generated when we
